hands_on_practices.solution:
We seek the point of first intersection of the $+$ characteristics.  Along a $+$ characteristic issued from $x_0$ we have
$$J_{+}(x_0)=u+2c,\quad J_{-}=-2c_{0},$$
so
$$u(x_0)=\frac{J_{+}+J_{-}}{2}
=\frac{2c_{0}+\alpha e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}}-2c_{0}}{2}
=\frac{\alpha}{2}e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}},$$
$$c(x_0)=\frac{J_{+}-J_{-}}{4}
=\frac{2c_{0}+\alpha e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}}+2c_{0}}{4}
=c_{0}+\frac{\alpha}{4}e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}}.$$
Hence the characteristic speed is
$$\lambda_{+}(x_0)
=u+c
=c_{0}+\frac{3\alpha}{4}e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}},$$
and the ray satisfies
$$x(t;x_0)
=x_0+c_{0}t+\frac{3\alpha}{4}e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}}\,t.$$
Shock forms when 
$$\frac{\partial x}{\partial x_0}
=1-\frac{3\alpha}{2}\frac{x_0t}{L^{2}}e^{-x_0^{2}/L^{2}}
=0
\;\Longrightarrow\;
t=\frac{2L^{2}}{3\alpha x_0}e^{x_0^{2}/L^{2}}.$$
Minimizing $t(x_0)$ gives
$$\frac{dt}{dx_0}=0
\;\Longrightarrow\;
x_0=\frac{L}{\sqrt2},$$
hence
$$t_{\rm shock}
=\frac{2L^{2}}{3\alpha (L/\sqrt2)}e^{1/2}
=\frac{2\sqrt2\,L}{3\alpha}e^{1/2}.$$
Finally

$$
x_{\rm shock}
=x_0+c_{0}t_{\rm shock}+\frac{3\alpha}{4}e^{-1/2}t_{\rm shock}
=\frac{L}{\sqrt2}+c_{0}\frac{2\sqrt2\,L}{3\alpha}e^{1/2}
+\frac{\sqrt2\,L}{2}
=\sqrt2\,L\Bigl(1+\frac{2c_{0}e^{1/2}}{3\alpha}\Bigr).
$$
